---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { languageRows } from "../facts";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Languages · Squeezy"
  description="Graph-backed navigation across 13 language families and bounded fallback for unsupported files."
  active="languages"
>
  <section class="page-hero">
    <div class="page-hero-inner">
      <span class="eyebrow">language coverage</span>
      <h1>Graph-backed navigation for 13 language families.</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        Squeezy treats programming languages as first-class inputs. Supported
        files get local graph navigation for declarations, calls, references,
        hierarchy, body hits, and exact slices. Unsupported files still work
        through bounded search and reads, without graph confidence.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="matrix">
      {
        languageRows.map((row) => (
          <article class="matrix-row">
            <div>
              <h3>{row.name}</h3>
            </div>
            <p>{row.detail}</p>
            {row.status && <span class:list={["status-pill", row.status === "strong" ? "ok" : row.status === "emerging" ? "warning" : ""]}>{row.status}</span>}
          </article>
        ))
      }
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-header">
      <span class="eyebrow">known limitations</span>
      <h2>What graph navigation deliberately does not solve.</h2>
      <p>
        Squeezy's graph is local and tree-sitter-based. It is fast and
        deterministic, but it is not a type checker or a runtime model. The
        following items stay heuristic, external, or fallback by design.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="grid-3">
      <article class="card">
        <span class="label">dynamic dispatch</span>
        <h3>Runtime resolution</h3>
        <p>Virtual dispatch, interface satisfaction, dynamic attribute access, and reflection-style call resolution stay candidate-grade.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="card">
        <span class="label">type solving</span>
        <h3>Overloads and inference</h3>
        <p>Overload resolution, generic constraint solving, and full type inference are out of scope. Squeezy defers to compilers when the task needs them.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="card">
        <span class="label">build systems</span>
        <h3>Macros, generated code, templates</h3>
        <p>Macro expansion, code generation, template instantiation, and complex preprocessor state are evidence for fallback, not exact compiler state.</p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section band">
    <div class="section-header">
      <span class="eyebrow">graph coverage</span>
      <h2>Language-aware indexing narrows the starting question.</h2>
      <p>
        Language-aware indexing is what makes cost savings concrete. The model
        can start with local declarations, relationships, calls, references,
        workspace facts, and changed-code context instead of reading broad file
        sets into paid context.
      </p>
      <div class="actions">
        <a class="button" href="/docs/semantic-navigation/" data-track-click="languages_graph_docs">
          Graph docs
        </a>
        <a class="button secondary" href="/docs/cost-receipts/" data-track-click="languages_cost_docs">
          Cost &amp; receipts
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
